There was no explosion on board the Boeing that crashed in Indonesia.
The Lion Air Boeing 737 that crashed on October 29 crashed into the sea at high speed.
The head of Indonesia's National Transportation Safety Committee, Surjanto Tandjono, denied reports of an explosion on board the plane.
According to the information received by the experts from the recording device on board the crew ("black box"), the aircraft was operating at full power when it crashed into the sea.
The conclusion about the circumstances of the plane crash was also made by looking at how the debris of the plane lay in the water.
The debris fell within a radius of 500 meters.
The Boeing 737 belonging to the Indonesian Lion Air company was flying from Jakarta to Pangkal Pinang.
The plane disappeared from radar 13 minutes after takeoff and crashed into the Java Sea between Sumatra and West Java.
All 189 people on board were killed.
The "black box" of the plane was found on November 1.
Rescuers are looking for a second recorder of the crew's speech.
The cause of the crash is still unknown.
The aircraft was built in 2018.
